    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-17T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-17T10:00:00-05:00" n="442"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d442">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5131/1887: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-17T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 17, 1939—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 17—3:24 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2493. Embassy’s telegrams 2160, September 25, 6 p.m. and 2227, September 28, 4
                        p.m.<note n="27" xml:id="d442fn27">Neither printed.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0504" n="496" xml:id="pg_496"/>
                <p>Bousquet told Fullerton today in the course of a conversation relating to other
                    questions that the French Government was increasingly anxious to open
                    negotiations leading to a revision of the trade agreement at such time as the
                    neutrality act might be modified. He said that it was his view that considerable
                    concessions should be made by the French Government in the nature of derogations
                    from existing import prohibitions in favor of American goods. He said that the
                    French Government still felt that the negotiations if and when entered into
                    should take place in France and that if the situation did not permit them to be
                    held in Paris they might be held in Langeais (Tours area).</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
